There is a power in selective attention.

Humans can’t process everything at once, so every achievement requires a kind of blindness. The archer ignores the crowd and sees the target. The entrepreneur ignores a thousand opinions and focuses on the product. The athlete ignores discomfort and focuses on the next rep.

But there are two versions of what you’re describing:

Focus

“I know the rest exists, but I choose not to spend energy on it right now.”

and

Fixation

“The rest no longer exists to me.”

The first creates agency.

The second creates vulnerability.

That’s why it’s dangerous.

Many of the most effective people in history possessed an almost unnatural ability to disregard noise, criticism, uncertainty, and competing demands. Their blinders gave them tremendous momentum. The same blinders also caused some of them to drive straight into cliffs.

A useful metaphor is horse blinders. They aren’t there because the horse is weak. They’re there because too much information can paralyze motion.

The trick is remembering that blinders are a tool, not an identity.

Put them on when charging.

Take them off when navigating.

What you’re describing also has an interesting relationship with your Pantheon ideas. The Gardener must notice everything. The Excavator must wander. But the Architect often has to become temporarily uncaring about a thousand alternatives in order to build one thing that actually exists.

Not “I don’t care.”

More like:

“I care so much about this objective that everything else is temporarily demoted.”

That mindset can move mountains.

It can also miss the mountain directly in front of it.

The art is knowing when to switch modes.